Basic Definitions

We first define a framework for the visualizations.

Activation Functions and Their Derivatives

We start by implementing the activation functions and their derivatives.

# Section 2.1.1: logistic
FnLogistic <- function(z){
  return(1 / (1 + exp(-z)))
}
FnLogisticD <- function(z){
  logistic <- FnLogistic(z)
  return(logistic * (1 - logistic))
}
FnLogisticDD <- function(z){
  logistic <- FnLogistic(z)
  return(logistic * (1 - logistic) * (1 - 2 * logistic))
}
# Section 2.1.2: arctan
FnArctan <- function(z){
  return(atan(z))
}
FnArctanD <- function(z){
  return(1 / (1 + z^2))
}
FnArctanDD <- function(z){
  return(-2 * z / (1 + z^2)^2)
}
# Section 2.1.3: tanh
FnTanh <- function(z){
  return(tanh(z))
}
FnTanhD <- function(z){
  t <- FnTanh(z)
  return(1 - t^2)
}
FnTanhDD <- function(z){
  t <- FnTanh(z)
  return(-2 * t * (1 - t^2))
}
# Section 2.1.4: softsign
FnSoftsign <- function(z){
  return(z / (1 + abs(z)))
}
FnSoftsignD <- function(z){
  soft.abs <- abs(FnSoftsign(z))
  return((1 - soft.abs)^2)
}
FnSoftsignDD <- function(z){
  sg <- sign(z)
  soft.abs <- FnSoftsign(z)
  return(-2 * sg * (1 - soft.abs)^3)
}
# Section 2.2.1: linear
FnLinear <- function(z){
  return(z)
}
# Section 2.2.2: relu
FnRelu <- function(z){
  return(z * (z > 0))
}
# Section 2.2.3: leakyrelu
FnLeakyrelu <- function(z, a = 0.01){
  return(z * (z > 0) + a * z * (z < 0))
}
# Section 2.3.1: softplus
FnSoftplus <- function(z){
  return(log(1 + exp(z)))
}
FnSoftplusD <- function(z){
  return(FnLogistic(z))
}
FnSoftplusDD <- function(z){
  return(FnLogisticD(z))
}
# Section 2.3.2: elu
FnElu <- function(z, a = 1){
  # To avoid comp. of exp for z>=0
  # Note that ggplot evaluates the function for a vector,
  # which means that standard if ... else does not work
  ifelse(z >= 0, z, a * (exp(z) - 1))
}
# Section 2.3.3: swish
FnSwish <- function(z, a = 1){
  return(z * FnLogistic(a * z))
}
FnSwishD <- function(z, a = 1){
  swish <- a * FnSwish(z, a)
  logistic <- FnLogistic(a * z)
  return(swish + logistic * (1 - swish))
}
FnSwishDD <- function(z, a = 1){
  swish <- a * FnSwish(z, a)
  logistic <- FnLogistic(a * z)
  return(a * (swish + 2 * logistic * (1 - swish)) * (1 - logistic))
}

Plotting Setup

We now set specifications for the plotting. (The latex switch yields specifications, which I use for the paper.)

library(ggplot2)
LabXY <- function(latex = FALSE, derivative = FALSE){
  if (latex)
    if (derivative)
      return(c("$z$", "$f'[z]$"))
    else
      return(c("$z$", "$f[z]$"))
  else
    if (derivative)
      return(c("z", "f'[z]")) 
    else
      return(c("z", "f[z]")) 
}
LineSize <- function(latex = FALSE){
  if (latex)
    return(5)
  else 
    return(1.5) 
}
LabelFontSize <- function(latex = FALSE){
  if (latex)
    return(12)
  else 
    return(4) 
}
DashedLines <- function(latex = FALSE, legend = FALSE){
  if (latex)
    if (legend)
      return("BB")
    else
      return("FF")
  else 
    if (legend)
      return("32")
    else
      return("44")
}
DottedLines <- function(latex = FALSE, legend = FALSE){
  if (latex)
    if (legend)
      return("1F")
    else
      return("6F")
  else 
    if (legend)
      return("13")
    else
      return("13")
}
DotDashLines <- function(latex = FALSE, legend = FALSE){
  if (latex)
    if (legend)
      return("FF1F")
    else
      return("FF6F")
  else 
    if (legend)
      return("3313")
    else
      return("4414")
}

Comparisons Among Activation Functions

We now compare different activation functions.

Broad Overview

Sigmoid Functions

We now compare the sigmoid functions among each other (Figure 2 in the manuscript).

PlotSigmoid <- function(latex = FALSE, FUN1 = FnLogistic, FUN2 = FnArctan, FUN3 = FnTanh, FUN4 = FnSoftsign, derivative = FALSE){
  ggplot() +
    stat_function(fun      = FUN1, 
                  color    = "red",
                  size     = LineSize(latex),
                  linetype = DashedLines(latex)) + 
    stat_function(fun      = FUN2,
                  color    = "red",
                  size     = LineSize(latex),
                  linetype = DottedLines(latex)) + 
    stat_function(fun      = FUN3,
                  color    = "red",
                  size     = LineSize(latex),
                  linetype = DotDashLines(latex)) +
    stat_function(fun      = FUN4,
                  color    = "red",
                  size     = LineSize(latex),
                  linetype = "solid") + 
    scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(-8, -6, -4, -2, 0, 2, 4, 6, 8), 
                       limits = c(-8, 8)) +
    scale_y_continuous(breaks = c(-1, 0, 1), 
                       limits = c(-1.5, 1.5)) +
    labs(x = LabXY(latex      = latex,
                   derivative = derivative)[1], 
         y = LabXY(latex      = latex, 
                   derivative = derivative)[2]) + 
    theme(text = element_text(size = 30)) + 
    theme(axis.title.y = element_text(margin = margin(t = 0, r = 15, b = 0, l = 0)))
}
PlotSigmoid()

PlotSigmoid(FUN1 = FnLogisticD, FUN2 = FnArctanD, FUN3 = FnTanhD, FUN4 = FnSoftsignD, derivative = TRUE)

Logistic Sigmoid Function Versus Binary Step Function

We now support the interpretation of logistic as a smooth step function (Figure 3 in the manuscript).

PlotLogStep <- function(latex = FALSE){
  ggplot() +
    stat_function(fun      = FnLogistic,
                  color    = "red",
                  size     = LineSize(latex),
                  linetype = DashedLines(latex)) + 
    geom_segment(aes(x = -4, y = 0, xend = 0, yend = 0),
                 color    = "black",
                 size     = LineSize(latex),
                 lineend  = "round",
                 linetype = "solid") + 
    geom_segment(aes(x = 0, y = 0, xend = 0, yend = 1),
                 color    = "black",
                 size     = LineSize(latex),
                 lineend  = "round",
                 linetype = "solid") +
    geom_segment(aes(x = 0, y = 1, xend = 4, yend = 1),
                 color    = "black",
                 size     = LineSize(latex),
                 lineend  = "round",
                 linetype = "solid") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(-4, -3, -2, -1, 0, 1, 2, 3, 4), 
                     limits = c(-4, 4)) +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = c(0, 1), 
                     limits = c(0, 1)) +
  labs(x = LabXY(latex = latex)[1], 
       y = LabXY(latex = latex)[2]) + 
  theme(text = element_text(size = 30)) + 
  theme(axis.title.y = element_text(margin = margin(t = 0, r = 15, b = 0, l = 0)))
}

Swish Versus Relu

We now compare swish with relu (Figure 7 in the manuscript).

PlotSwishRelu <- function(latex = FALSE, derivative = FALSE){
  if (derivative == TRUE){
    Fun1 = FnSwishD
    Fun2 = function(z){return(1000)}
    upp  = 0
  }
  else{
    Fun1 = FnSwish
    Fun2 = FnRelu
    upp  = 1000
  }
  ggplot() +
    stat_function(fun      = Fun2,
                  color    = "blue",
                  size     = LineSize(latex),
                  linetype = "solid") +
    geom_segment(aes(x = -3, y = 0 + upp, xend = 0, yend = 0 + upp),
                   color    = "blue",
                   size     = LineSize(latex),
                   lineend  = "round",
                   linetype = "solid") + 
    geom_segment(aes(x = 0, y = 0 + upp, xend = 0, yend = 1 + upp),
                   color    = "blue",
                   size     = LineSize(latex),
                   lineend  = "round",
                   linetype = "solid") +
    geom_segment(aes(x = 0, y = 1 + upp , xend = 3, yend = 1 + upp),
                   color    = "blue",
                   size     = LineSize(latex),
                   lineend  = "round",
                   linetype = "solid") +
    stat_function(fun = function(z){return(Fun1(z, a = 1))}, 
                  color    = "black",
                  size     = LineSize(latex),
                  linetype = DottedLines(latex)) + 
    stat_function(fun      = function(z){return(Fun1(z, a = 5))},
                  color    = "black",
                  size     = LineSize(latex),
                  linetype = DashedLines(latex)) + 
    stat_function(fun = function(z){return(Fun1(z, a = 0.2))},
                  color    = "black",
                  size     = LineSize(latex),
                  linetype = DotDashLines(latex)) +
    scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(-3, -2, -1, 0, 1, 2, 3),
                       limits = c(-3, 3)) +
    scale_y_continuous(breaks = c(-1, 0, 1, 2, 3), 
                       limits = c(-1, 3)) +
    labs(x = LabXY(latex      = latex,
                   derivative = derivative)[1], 
         y = LabXY(latex      = latex, 
                   derivative = derivative)[2]) + 
    theme(text = element_text(size = 30)) + 
    theme(axis.title.y = element_text(margin = margin(t = 0, r = 15, b = 0, l = 0)))
}
PlotSwishRelu()

Output Ranges of the Functions and Their Derivatives

We now confirm some of the output ranges derived in the manuscript.

Output Ranges of Logistics Second Derivative

We first consider the second derivative of logistic (see Section 2.1.1 and Lemma A.1).

# Function minima and maxima from the manuscript
c(FnLogisticDD(log(2 + sqrt(3))), FnLogisticDD(log(2 - sqrt(3))))
## [1] -0.09622504  0.09622504
# Function minima and maxima from a numerical evaluation
c(optimize(FnLogisticDD, interval=c(-100, 100), maximum = FALSE)$objective, optimize(FnLogisticDD, interval=c(-100, 100), maximum = TRUE)$objective)
## [1] -0.09622504  0.09622504

Hence, the output domain of logistics second derivative is \([-0.096225, 0.096225]\), as stated in the paper.

Output Ranges of Swish and Its Derivatives

We then consider swish and its derivatives (see Section 2.3.3 and Section A.7.5). We first plot and calculate the values \(z_1\) and \(f_1[z_1]\) in Lemma A.10.

library("nleqslv")  # find a root of a linear equation
library(gridExtra)  # combine multiple plots
SwishRange <- function(z){
  return(1 + (1 + z) * exp(-z))
}
SwishRangeD <- function(z){
  return(2 - z + (2 + z) * exp(-z))
}
z1 <- nleqslv(-1, SwishRange)$x
f1 <- FnSwish(z = z1, a = 1)
z1P <- nleqslv(1, SwishRangeD)$x
f1P <- FnSwishD(z = z1P, a = 1)
z1N <- nleqslv(-3, SwishRangeD)$x
f1N <- FnSwishD(z = z1N, a = 1)
PlotSwishBounds <- function(derivative = FALSE)
{
  if (derivative){
    Fun1     <- SwishRangeD
    Fun2     <- FnSwishD
    z.value  <- z1P
    f.value  <- f1P
    lab1     <- "z1'"
    lab2     <- "-z1'"
    lab3     <- "f1'"
    lab4     <- "1-f1'"
    lab5     <- "2-z+(2+z)exp(-z)"
    z.valueN <- z1N
    f.valueN <- f1N
  }
  else{
    Fun1     <- SwishRange
    Fun2     <- FnSwish
    z.value  <-  z1
    f.value  <- f1
    lab1     <- "z1"
    lab2     <- ""
    lab3     <- "f1"
    lab4     <- ""
    lab5     <- "1+(1+z)exp(-z)"
    z.valueN <- 0
    f.valueN <- 0
  }
  p1 <- ggplot() +
          geom_segment(aes(x = -3, y = 0, xend = 3, yend = 0),
                       color = "grey50",
                       size  = 1) +
          geom_segment(aes(x = z.value, y = -3, xend = z.value, yend = 2.7),
                       color = "grey50",
                       size  = 0.3) +
          geom_segment(aes(x = z.valueN, y = -3, xend = z.valueN, yend = 2.7),
                       color = "grey50",
                       size = 0.3) +
          geom_segment(aes(x = 0, y = -3, xend = 0, yend = 3),
                       color = "grey50",
                       size  = 1) +
          stat_function(fun  = Fun1,
                        size = LineSize(FALSE)) +
          annotate("text", x = z.value, y = 3, color= "grey50", label = lab1, size = LabelFontSize(FALSE)) +
          annotate("text", x = z.valueN, y = 3, color= "grey50", label = lab2, size = LabelFontSize(FALSE)) +
          scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(-3, -2, -1, 0, 1, 2, 3), 
                             limits = c(-3, 3)) +
          scale_y_continuous(breaks = c(-3, -2, -1, 0, 1, 2, 3), 
                             limits = c(-3, 3)) +
          labs(x = "z", 
               y = lab5)
  p2 <- ggplot() +
          geom_segment(aes(x = -3, y = 0, xend = 3, yend = 0),
                       color = "grey50",
                       size  = 1) +
          geom_segment(aes(x = z.value, y = -3, xend = z.value, yend = 2.7),
                       color = "grey50",
                       size  = 0.3) +
          geom_segment(aes(x = z.valueN, y = -3, xend = z.valueN, yend = 2.7),
                       color = "grey50",
                       size  = 0.3) +
          geom_segment(aes(x = -3, y = f.value, xend = 2.7, yend = f.value),
                       color = "grey50",
                       size  = 0.3) +
          geom_segment(aes(x = -3, y = f.valueN, xend = 2.7, yend = f.valueN),
                       color = "grey50",
                       size  = 0.3) +
          geom_segment(aes(x = 0, y = -3, xend = 0, yend = 3),
                       color = "grey50",
                       size  = 1) +
          stat_function(fun  = Fun2,
                        size = LineSize(FALSE)) +
          annotate("text", x = z.value, y = 3, color= "grey50", label = lab1, size = LabelFontSize(FALSE)) +
          annotate("text", x = z.valueN, y = 3, color= "grey50", label = lab2, size = LabelFontSize(FALSE)) +
          annotate("text", x = 3, y = f.value + 0.25, color= "grey50", label = lab3, size = LabelFontSize(FALSE)) +
          annotate("text", x = 3, y = f.valueN - 0.25, color= "grey50", label = lab4, size = LabelFontSize(FALSE)) +
          scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(-3, -2, -1, 0, 1, 2, 3), 
                             limits = c(-3, 3)) +
          scale_y_continuous(breaks = c(-3, -2, -1, 0, 1, 2, 3), 
                             limits = c(-3, 3)) +
          labs(x = "z", 
               y = "f1[z]")
  grid.arrange(p1, p2, heights = c(1), ncol = 2)
  print(c(z.value, f.value))
}
PlotSwishBounds(derivative = FALSE)

## [1] -1.2784645 -0.2784645

We find that \(z_1\approx\)-1.2784645 and \(f_1[z_1]\approx\)-0.2784645.

We can now confirm the dependencies of the minimizers and minima of swish on \(a\) stated in the manuscript.

SwishTest <- function(a = 1, derivative = "none"){
  if (derivative == "none"){
    za <- optim(0, FnSwish, a = a)$par
    fa <- FnSwish(z = za, a = a)
    return(c(z1 / za, f1 / fa))
  }
  if (derivative == "first"){
    zaN <- optim(0, FnSwishD, a = a)$par
    faN <- FnSwishD(z = zaN, a = a)
    return(c(z1N / zaN, f1N / faN))
  }
}
a1 <- 0.5; a2 <- 1; a3 <- 2
c(SwishTest(a1) / a1,SwishTest(a2) / a2 ,SwishTest(a3) / a3)   # should all be close to 1
## [1] 1 1 1 1 1 1

We now plot and calculate the values \(z_1'\) and \(f_1[z_1']\) in Lemma A.11.

PlotSwishBounds(derivative = TRUE)

## [1] 2.399357 1.099839

We find that \(z_1'\approx\) 2.3993573 and \(\dot f_1[z_1']\approx\) 1.0998393.

We can also verify that the minimizers scale with \(1/a\) and the minima are constant in \(a\).

c(SwishTest(a1, derivative = "first")[1] / a1,
  SwishTest(a1, derivative = "first")[2],
  SwishTest(a2, derivative = "first")[1] / a2,
  SwishTest(a2, derivative = "first")[2],
  SwishTest(a3, derivative = "first")[1] / a3, 
  SwishTest(a3, derivative = "first")[2])  # should all be close to 1
## [1] 1.000058 1.000000 1.000058 1.000000 1.000058 1.000000

We finally turn to the second derivatives. We first confirm the ranges stated in the manuscript.

Fun1 <- function(z){FnSwishDD(z, a = a1)}
Fun2 <- function(z){FnSwishDD(z, a = a2)}
Fun3 <- function(z){FnSwishDD(z, a = a3)}
# Maxima
cPP <- optim(0, function(z){FnSwishDD(z, a = 1)}, control=list(fnscale=-1))$value  # last argument ensures maximization
print(cPP)
## [1] 0.5
c(optim(0, Fun1, control=list(fnscale=-1))$value / a1,
  optim(0, Fun2, control=list(fnscale=-1))$value / a2, 
  optim(0, Fun3, control=list(fnscale=-1))$value / a3) / cPP  # should all be close to 1
## [1] 1 1 1
# Minima
cNN <- optim(0, function(z){FnSwishDD(z, a = 1)})$value
print(cNN)
## [1] -0.03691437
c(optim(0, Fun1)$value / a1,
  optim(0, Fun2)$value / a2, 
  optim(0, Fun3)$value / a3) / cNN  # should all be close to 1
## [1] 1 1 1

We confirm that the maxima of swishs second derivative are 0.5\(\cdot a\), and the minima are approximately -0.0369144\(\cdot a\).
